If $\theta$ is the angle between the vectors $\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} 12 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$, then find $\cos \theta$.
inference:
The dot product of two vectors $\begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} b_1 \\ b_2 \end{pmatrix}$ is $a_1b_1 + a_2b_2$.

The magnitude of a vector $\begin{pmatrix} a_1 \\ a_2 \end{pmatrix}$ is $\sqrt{a_1^2 + a_2^2}$.

The cosine of the angle between two vectors is the dot product of the vectors divided by the product of their magnitudes.

So, $\cos \theta = \frac{\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 12 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}}{\left\Vert \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix} \right\Vert \left\Vert \begin{pmatrix} 12 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \right\Vert} = \frac{36 - 20}{\sqrt{3^2 + (-4)^2} \sqrt{12^2 + 5^2}} = \frac{16}{\sqrt{25} \sqrt{169}} = \frac{16}{5 \cdot 13} = \frac{16}{65}$.

Final Answer: $\boxed{\frac{16}{65}}$. I hope it is correct.
